# AI Procurement Policy

**{{ business_name }}**
*Effective Date: {{ effective_date }}*
*Version: {{ version }}*

---

## 1. Purpose

This policy establishes the evaluation, approval, and onboarding process for acquiring new AI tools and services at {{ business_name }}. It ensures that AI procurement decisions account for privacy obligations under the **Privacy Act 1988**, transparency requirements under the **POLA Act 2024**, and governance expectations from the **AI6 Guidance for AI Adoption** (October 2024).

---

## 2. Scope

This policy applies to:

- Purchase or subscription to any AI-powered software, platform, or API
- Free-tier or trial usage of AI tools that process organisational or personal data
- Open-source AI models deployed on {{ business_name }}'s infrastructure
- AI features embedded in existing software (e.g., AI assistants in productivity suites)
- AI tools used by contractors or third parties on {{ business_name }}'s behalf

**Shadow AI note:** Using AI tools without following this procurement process constitutes Shadow AI and is governed by the {{ business_name }} AI Acceptable Use Policy.

---

## 3. Pre-Procurement Assessment

Before any AI tool is evaluated, the requester must complete an **AI Procurement Request** addressing:

### 3.1 Business Case

| Question | Response Required |
|----------|-------------------|
| What business problem does this AI tool solve? | Description |
| What data will the tool process? | Data types from classification policy |
| Will the tool process personal information? | Yes / No |
| Will the tool make or assist decisions affecting individuals? | Yes / No |
| Who will have access to the tool? | Roles and headcount |
| What is the expected annual cost? | Budget estimate |

### 3.2 Risk Screening

The following triggers require escalation to {{ ai_governance_contact if ai_governance_contact else "the AI governance contact" }} before proceeding:

- The tool will process **Confidential** or **Restricted** data
- The tool will process data of **children under 18**
{% if "Health Information" in data_types_processed %}- The tool will process **health information**{% endif %}
- The tool processes data **overseas** (triggers APP 8 assessment)
- The tool makes **automated decisions** affecting individuals (triggers POLA Act assessment)
- The tool is **free-tier** or **open-source** with unclear data handling terms

---

## 4. Evaluation Criteria

All AI tools must be evaluated against the following criteria before approval:

### 4.1 Privacy and Data Protection

| Criterion | Requirement | Weight |
|-----------|------------|--------|
| Data processing location | Identify all data centre locations | High |
| Data residency | Australian data hosting preferred for Confidential/Restricted data | High |
| Model training opt-out | Vendor must offer opt-out from using customer data for model training | Critical |
| Sub-processor disclosure | Vendor must disclose all sub-processors and their locations | High |
| Data deletion capability | Vendor must support data deletion on request with written confirmation | High |
| Encryption | Data encrypted in transit (TLS 1.2+) and at rest (AES-256) | High |

### 4.2 Contractual Requirements

Before signing, the following must be verified:

- [ ] **Data Processing Agreement (DPA)** — covers APP 8 obligations for overseas processing
- [ ] **Model training opt-out** — confirmed in writing, not just in generic terms
- [ ] **Sub-processor list** — provided and reviewed
- [ ] **Incident notification** — vendor commits to notifying within 72 hours of a data breach
- [ ] **Data return/deletion** — clear terms for data portability and destruction on contract end
- [ ] **IP ownership** — AI outputs generated using {{ business_name }}'s data belong to {{ business_name }}
- [ ] **Liability and indemnification** — vendor accepts liability for data breaches caused by their systems
- [ ] **Insurance** — vendor maintains adequate cyber insurance

### 4.3 Security Assessment

| Criterion | Acceptable Evidence |
|-----------|-------------------|
| Security certification | SOC 2 Type II, ISO 27001, or equivalent |
| Penetration testing | Annual third-party pentest report |
| Access controls | Role-based access, MFA, SSO support |
| Audit logging | Comprehensive logs available to customer |
| Vulnerability management | Defined patching cadence |

### 4.4 AI-Specific Assessment

| Criterion | Requirement |
|-----------|------------|
| Model transparency | Vendor discloses model type, version, and known limitations |
| Bias testing | Vendor provides bias/fairness testing results where applicable |
| Output accuracy | Vendor provides accuracy/hallucination benchmarks for the use case |
| Human override | Tool supports human review and override of AI decisions |
| Explainability | Tool can explain or justify its outputs when required |

